Email 3: Compliance & Zero-Knowledge Security (Sent Day 8)

Subject: The Cryptographic Shield: How zero-knowledge architecture protects your practice
Preheader: Under HIPAA, the FTC Safeguards Rule, or ABA Ethics, compliance is your shield.

Dear {{ recipient_name|default('there') }},

Whether your firm is subject to the HIPAA Security Rule (healthcare), the FTC Safeguards Rule & IRS Pub 4557 (tax/accounting), or ABA Model Rule 1.6(c) (legal), you have a federal and ethical obligation to safeguard customer data in transit and at rest.

Standard email is not secure. But what makes FileDrop Pro different from standard cloud storage?

It comes down to Zero-Knowledge, End-to-End Encryption (E2EE).

How your secure envelope works:

Most cloud providers encrypt your files, but they hold the decryption keys. If their databases are breached, your clients' private tax records, medical charts, or legal evidence are exposed, and your firm is liable.

FileDrop Pro uses a local double-envelope cryptographic system:

When a client drops a file, their browser generates a unique, symmetric AES-256 session key ($K_{sym}$) to encrypt the document locally in memory.

That key is immediately wrapped ("encrypted") using your firm's asymmetric Public Key ($K_{pub}$):

$$WrappedKey = \text{RSA-OAEP}(K_{sym} \text{ using } K_{pub})$$

The encrypted file is sent directly to AWS S3, and the wrapped key is stored in our database.

Our servers never touch the raw session key. When you open the file, your browser decrypts the wrapped key locally using your private master password, keeping your data entirely secure from external threats.

